b'' b'boylan) wrote:' b'' b'' b' yes, i know computers and harddisk drives should be always on. but what about' b" monitors? they generate a lots of heat. should i or shouldn't i keep them on" b' hours a day? any advice? thanks. take care...paul' b'' b' there has been no empirical evidence to support the first statement. true,' b' there is a power surge at startup that has the potential to do damage, but' b" the internal power supply is well-protected. (i've turned my mac on and off" b' six or seven times a day for three years without problem). the monitor is' b' the same. to leave it on is to waste a lot of electricity twice as much' b' as a television, possibly more.' b'' b" turn it off when you're not using it. it'll save you money and the world" b' a few more resources.' b'' b'the problem with turing your computer on and off constantly is not due to' b'the power surge at start up. it is due to thermal fatigue. you turn on' b'your computer, it heats up, and everything expands. you turn it off, it' b'cools off, and everything contracts. there is a limited number of cycles' b'of this that any component can take before it fails. modern electronics' b'are much more robust in this respect than their predeccesors. in fact' b'portable computers are designed with this in mind since the sleep function' b'that extends battery life also greatly increaces the number of thermal' b'cycles that occur. as a rule of thumb, if i am not going to use my' b'computer (and this includes the monitor) in the next hours, i turn it' b'off (i always dim the monitor when not in use to prolong the life of the' b'phosphor). i tend to think that with the pace of technical innovation in' b'the computer industry you should be much less concerned with the fatigue' b'life of your equipment and more concerned with how long your particular' b'architecture will be supported by hardware and software vendors. b'' b'charles kuehmann' b'northwestern university' b'steel research group' 